## Purpose
Add proper loading and error states to the project list page. Good loading/error UX is essential for a polished feel and helps users understand system state.

## Loading State

### Skeleton Cards
Show placeholder cards that match the shape of real project cards:
```typescript
function ProjectCardSkeleton() {
  return (
    <div className="flex items-center gap-3 px-3 py-2.5 animate-pulse">
      {/* Icon placeholder */}
      <div className="w-8 h-8 rounded-md bg-secondary" />

      {/* Content placeholder */}
      <div className="flex-1 space-y-2">
        <div className="h-4 w-32 bg-secondary rounded" />
        <div className="h-3 w-48 bg-secondary rounded" />
      </div>

      {/* Right side placeholder */}
      <div className="h-4 w-4 bg-secondary rounded" />
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Integration
```typescript
if (isLoading) {
  return (
    <div className="border border-border rounded-md overflow-hidden divide-y divide-border">
      <ProjectCardSkeleton />
      <ProjectCardSkeleton />
      <ProjectCardSkeleton />
    </div>
  );
}
```

Show 3 skeleton cards as a reasonable default. This provides visual structure while loading without being jarring.

## Error State

### Error Display
```typescript
function ProjectListError({ message, onRetry }: { message: string; onRetry: () => void }) {
  return (
    <div className="border border-border rounded-md p-8 text-center">
      {/* Error icon */}
      <div className="w-12 h-12 rounded-full bg-destructive/10 flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-4">
        <AlertCircle className="h-6 w-6 text-destructive" />
      </div>

      {/* Message */}
      <h3 className="font-medium mb-1">Failed to load projects</h3>
      <p className="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-4">{message}</p>

      {/* Retry */}
      <Button variant="outline" onClick={onRetry}>
        <RefreshCw className="h-4 w-4 mr-2" />
        Try Again
      </Button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Integration
```typescript
if (error) {
  return (
    <ProjectListError 
      message={error.message} 
      onRetry={() => refetch()} 
    />
  );
}
```

## Error Scenarios
- **Network error**: "Failed to fetch" - server might be down
- **Server error**: 500 response - show generic message
- **Config error**: Could indicate corrupted config file

For all cases, the retry button is the primary action. If errors persist, users should check the server logs.

## Refetching State
When data exists but is being refetched (background refresh), don't show loading state - keep showing current data. React Query handles this automatically with `isLoading` (initial load) vs `isFetching` (refetch).

```typescript
// Only show skeleton on initial load, not refetch
if (isLoading) {
  return <SkeletonState />;
}

// Show error only if no cached data
if (error && !projects) {
  return <ErrorState />;
}
```

## Page-Level Integration
```typescript
export default function ProjectListPage() {
  const { data: projects, isLoading, error, refetch } = useProjects();
  const [folderBrowserOpen, setFolderBrowserOpen] = useState(false);

  return (
    <div className="min-h-screen bg-background">
      {/* Header - always shown */}
      <header>...</header>

      <main className="max-w-3xl mx-auto p-4">
        <div className="mb-6">
          <h1>Projects</h1>
          <p>Select a project to view swarms and sessions</p>
        </div>

        {isLoading ? (
          <ProjectListSkeleton />
        ) : error && !projects ? (
          <ProjectListError message={error.message} onRetry={refetch} />
        ) : !projects?.length ? (
          <NoProjects onAddProject={() => setFolderBrowserOpen(true)} />
        ) : (
          <ProjectList projects={projects} />
        )}
      </main>

      <FolderBrowserModal 
        open={folderBrowserOpen}
        onOpenChange={setFolderBrowserOpen}
      />
    </div>
  );
}
```

