## Purpose
Implement the `GET /api/projects` endpoint that returns all saved projects with computed fields and validation status.

## Why This Endpoint?
This is the primary data source for the project list UI. It must:
1. Return all projects from config
2. Compute display-friendly fields (displayPath, displayName)
3. Validate each project's path still exists
4. Sort by most recently added

## Response Schema
```typescript
interface ProjectsResponse {
  projects: Project[];
}

interface Project {
  id: string;
  path: string;              // Absolute: /Users/erik/dev/project
  displayPath: string;       // Friendly: ~/dev/project
  name: string | null;       // Custom name or null
  displayName: string;       // name ?? derived from path
  addedAt: string;           // ISO 8601
  status: "active" | "missing";
}
```

## Implementation
```typescript
// src/app/api/projects/route.ts
import { NextResponse } from "next/server";
import { configService } from "@/lib/services/config";
import fs from "fs/promises";

export async function GET() {
  try {
    const projects = await configService.getProjects();

    const enrichedProjects = await Promise.all(
      projects.map(async (p) => {
        // Check if path exists
        let status: "active" | "missing" = "active";
        try {
          await fs.access(p.path);
        } catch {
          status = "missing";
        }

        return {
          id: p.id,
          path: p.path,
          displayPath: configService.toDisplayPath(p.path),
          name: p.name,
          displayName: p.name ?? configService.deriveDisplayName(p.path),
          addedAt: p.addedAt,
          status,
        };
      })
    );

    // Sort by addedAt descending (most recent first)
    enrichedProjects.sort((a, b) => 
      new Date(b.addedAt).getTime() - new Date(a.addedAt).getTime()
    );

    return NextResponse.json({ projects: enrichedProjects });
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Failed to fetch projects:", error);
    return NextResponse.json(
      { error: "Failed to fetch projects" },
      { status: 500 }
    );
  }
}
```

## Performance Note
Path validation (`fs.access`) is done for each project on every request. For typical use cases (< 20 projects), this is fine. If it becomes slow, we could:
- Cache validation results briefly
- Validate asynchronously and update status in background
- Only validate on explicit refresh

For v1, keep it simple - validate on every request.

